@node Introduction

@{line}@{u}Introduction@{uu}@{par}

The @{b}Amiga Magneto-Optical Drive FAQ@{ub} contains information about using
@{"magneto-optical (MO) disk drives" link What_are} with Amiga computers. It is
freely distributable providing no changes are made.@{par}

(In case you're not familiar with the acronym, FAQ stands for @{i}Frequently
Asked Questions@{ui}. Compilations of information about various subjects on the
Internet are commonly referred to as FAQs.)@{par}

I hope the availability of this document will encourage more Amiga users to
consider optical storage, instead of fragile magnetic media like
@{"Zip, Jaz" link Zip_Jaz_Problems} and SyQuest.@{par}

Please @{"contact me" link Contacting} if you have any comments, suggestions or
questions about this document or MO drives and media.@{par}

@endnode


@node What_are "What are Magneto-Optical Disk Drives?"

@{line}@{u}What are Magneto-Optical Disk Drives?@{uu}@{par}

Magneto-optical ("MO") disk drives are versatile removable storage devices,
which use very robust and @{"inexpensive media" link Media_Costs}. You can use
an MO disk just like a large floppy disk, or like a hard disk. 3½" MO disks
can store up to 1.3GB, and 5¼" MO disks can store up to 5.2GB. There are many
@{"advantages" link Advantages} in using MO disks instead of other types of
media.@{par}

The @{"How MO Drives Work" link How_MO_Drives_Work} section explains how data
is written to and read from MO disks.@{par}

MO uses similar technology to Sony's increasingly popular Mini Disc format. If
you have used Mini Discs before, you will have some idea how rugged and
reliable MO disks are.@{par}

In Japan MO drives are very popular, more so than Iomega's Zip drives (which
seem to be inexplicably common in the West).@{par}

MO drives are available as internal or external, SCSI or IDE/ATAPI drives. MO
drives with USB and FireWire (IEEE 1394) interfaces have been introduced
recently. As yet there is no way of connecting USB or FireWire peripherals to
Amigas however.@{par}

MO "jukeboxes" are also available, but these are intended for business use as
they are expensive, and few Amiga users need to store hundreds of gigabytes of
data. Also, special driver software would be required and none exists for the
Amiga.@{par}

@endnode


@node Advantages "Advantages of Magneto-Optical Storage"

@{line}@{u}Advantages of Magneto-Optical Storage@{uu}@{par}

Magneto-Optical storage has many advantages over other types of removable media:@{par}
@{lindent 4}@{pari -2}@{par}· Media life is at least 30 years, which greatly
exceeds that of magnetic media like floppy disks, Zip and Jaz disks. Some
manufacturers quote media life of 50 or even 100 years. Data can be rewritten
at least a million times, and read at least 10 million times; some
manufacturers quote figures ten times this. This figure also exceeds that for
magnetic media.@{line}@{par}
· There is no physical contact between disk surface and drive head, so there is
no possibility of data loss through a head crash.@{line}@{par}
· MO drives are @{"backwardly compatible" link Backward_Compatibility}, which
means that if you upgrade your drive in the future, you will be able to read
and write all your existing disks on the new drive.@{line}@{par}
· MO disks are not susceptible to magnetic fields.@{line}@{par}
· If, for example, you spill a cup of coffee on an MO disk, you can clean the
disk surface and continue to use the disk. @{"Cleaning kits" link Maintenance} are
available for both MO drives and disks.@{line}@{par}
· MO disks are simple in construction, unlike some other kinds of removable
media which may contain moving parts. This is another reason why MO offers
greater reliability than magnetic media.@{line}@{par}
· MO disks are available in several
@{"different capacities" link Types_of_MO_Media}, which vary in
@{"price" link Media_Costs}. Cost per megabyte is much lower than all other
kinds of random access removable media.@{line}@{par}
· Unlike Zip, Jaz, SyQuest etc., MO drives and disks are not proprietary; they
are made by many companies. The disks are covered by various international
standards. So you will not be stuck if your drive manufacturer goes bust, as
happened recently to SyQuest.@{line}@{par}
· Compared to other forms of optical storage, there are no restrictions on
writing and rewriting data to MO disks, unlike CD-R or CD-RW. Also unlike CD-R
& CD-RW, since the disk itself is protected by a plastic casing there is no
danger of data corruption due to the disk getting scratched.@{line}@{par}
· MO drives normally automatically verify written data to guarantee data
integrity. There is no such verification with CD-R, CD-RW or most types of
magnetic media, so to be assured that the data has been written properly when
using these, you would need to manually compare all copied files.@{line}@{par}
· MO drives have much shorter seek times than PD and DVD-RAM drives.@{line}@{par}
· Magneto-optical technology is well-proven. I believe the first ISO standard
5¼" MO drives were released in 1989 or 1990, with 128MB 3½" MO drives becoming
available in 1991. 640MB 3½" drives have been available since 1996. Originally
MO was largely restricted to professional use due to high drive cost, but over
the past couple of years this situation has changed.@{line}@{par}
· MO disks are convenient, compact and easy to use. 3½" MO disks are the same
size as two floppy disks stacked on top of each other. They have a
write-protect tab which works just like a floppy disk's.@{pard}@{par}

@endnode


@node Pictures "Pictures of MO Drives and Disks"

@{line}@{u}Pictures of MO Drives and Disks@{uu}@{par}

This section contains some pictures of magneto-optical drives and disks, so
you can see what they look like. You need to have a JPEG datatype installed in
order to see these within MultiView. Alternatively you can use any JPEG viewer
to display the images manually; they are in the Images drawer.@{par}

@{code}@{jcenter}@{"    3½ inch transparent MO disk     " link Images/3½_MO.jpg/main}
@{"          5¼ inch MO disks          " link Images/5¼_MO.jpg/main}
@{" Olympus PowerMO 230II drive & disk " link Images/PowerMO_230II_and_disk.jpg/main}
