@endnode


@node How_MO_Drives_Work "How MO Drives Work"

@{line}@{u}How MO Drives Work@{uu}@{par}

This section describes the theory of operation of MO drives. It is quite
technical; it is not necessary to understand this in order to use a
magneto-optical drive.@{par}

Magneto-optical drives use, as the name suggests, both magnetic and optical
effects to read and write data. A layer within the media contains magnetically
sensitive elements. When this layer is heated to its "Curie point", about
200°C, the polarity of the magnetic elements can be changed by an external
magnetic field from the drive head.@{par}

To write data, on normal media two disk revolutions are needed. On the first
revolution, a magnetic field is applied and the laser heats up the target area
of the disk to its Curie point. This causes the magnetic elements to all align
themselves parallel with the magnetic field. This effectively erases the target
area, recording all 0 bits. On the next revolution of the disk, the magnetic
field is reversed, and the laser heats up only those areas which are to have 1s
recorded.@{par}

Because the written magnetic polarity is "frozen into" the disk, MO disks are
not susceptible to magnetic fields as magnetic media are.@{par}

Data is read from the disk in a purely optical way. The laser is used at a low
power which does not heat the disk. Depending on the recorded magnetic
polarity, the polarity of the laser light reflected from the disk is rotated a
few degrees either way. This rotation is called the Kerr effect. The drive
detects this, and thus determines whether a 0 or 1 was read.@{par}


@{b}LIMDOW Media@{ub}@{par}

Use of @{"LIMDOW media" link LIMDOW} significantly improves write speeds.
LIMDOW-capable drives can read and write to conventional MO disks too.@{par}

When a LIMDOW disk is inserted, the drive detects this and enables additional
control over the laser. LIMDOW disks have a different composition to normal
media, which makes it possible to rewrite data in a single revolution rather
than the two required by conventional disks.@{par}

The drive records data by heating areas of the disk to their Curie point, as
with conventional media. However, depending on the laser beam power, the
magnetic element orients itself with either the external magnetic field or with
a reference layer that is built into the disk. Thus data can be written in a
single pass.@{par}

Data is read from LIMDOW media in the same way as from conventional media.@{par}

@endnode


@node Types_of_MO_Media "Types of MO Media"

@{line}@{u}Types of MO Media@{uu}@{par}

There are two physical media sizes, 3½" and 5¼". This document concentrates in
some places on 3½" drives and media, since 3½" MO drives are cheaper than 5¼"
ones, and I have had less experience with 5¼" drives.@{par}

A 3½ MO disk looks similar to a 3½" floppy disk, except twice as thick. There
is a metal shutter covering the disk surface, and a write-protect tab in the
corner, just like a floppy disk. If you open the shutter, the disk inside has a
similar appearance to the surface of a CD.
@{"Click here" link Images/3½_MO.jpg/main} to see a picture of a 3½" MO disk,
and @{"here" link Images/5¼_MO.jpg/main} for a picture of some 5¼" MO disks.@{par}

Whilst there are two physical disk sizes, there are several different disk
capacities. 3½" MO disks are currently available in the these capacities:
@{lindent 4}@{pari -2}@{par}· 128MB (512-byte sectors)@{par}
· 230MB (512-byte sectors)@{par}
· 540MB (512-byte sectors), 640MB (2048-byte sectors)@{par}
· 1.3GB (2048-byte sectors)@{pard}@{par}

5¼" MO disks are currently available in these capacities:
@{lindent 4}@{pari -2}@{par}· 600MB (512-byte sectors), 650MB (1024-byte sectors)@{par}
· 1.2GB (512-byte sectors), 1.3GB (1024-byte sectors)@{par}
· 2.3GB (512-byte sectors), 2.6GB (1024-byte sectors)@{par}
· 4.1GB (512-byte sectors), 4.8GB (1024-byte sectors), 5.2GB (2048-byte sectors)@{pard}@{par}

The only difference between 540MB and 640MB 3½" MO disks is the sector size. It
is 512 bytes for 128MB, 230MB and 540MB disks, but 2048 bytes for 640MB disks.
There is no real advantage to Amiga users in buying 540MB disks if you have a
640MB drive, unless you for some reason want to use a FastFileSystem version
earlier than 40.1 (see the @{"Amiga Requirements" link Amiga_Requirements} section),
or use an operating system which does not support sector sizes greater than 512
bytes, such as NetBSD. Also, performance of 512-byte-sectors media with
Macintosh emulators or a real Mac or PC computer may be better. A similar thing
applies to 5¼" MO disks, 600MB vs 650MB, 4.1GB vs 5.2GB, etc.@{par}

3½" MO disks are single-sided. 5¼" ones are double-sided, and half the quoted
capacity is accessed at a time. The disk is turned over to access the other
half.@{par}

MO media can be bought as unformatted, or formatted for MS-DOS or Macintosh. If
you're using a Mac emulator, you may wish to buy Mac formatted disks. For Amiga
use it doesn't matter; you can just do a Format QUICK on the disk to make it
ready for use, which only takes a few seconds.@{par}

MO disks are low-level formatted and usually certified at the factory.
Certified disks have had their surface checked and any bad sectors are
remapped. If you buy an uncertified disk (I don't know whether these are
available), it will be a good idea to @{"low-level format" link Low-Level} it
before use.@{par}

More recent disk capacities (230MB, 540MB and 640MB for 3½" disks) are also
available in @{"LIMDOW" link LIMDOW} variants, also known as "direct
overwrite". Writing to LIMDOW disks is faster than to normal disks.@{par}

In common with hard disk manufacturers, MO disk capacities are usually quoted
in @{i}millions of bytes@{ui}, as opposed to the usual computer terminology
where 1 megabyte = 1024×1024 = 1,048,576 bytes. The quoted figure is the
unformatted capacity. For example, the formatted capacity of a 640MB 3½" disk
is 635,600,896 bytes, which is just over 606 megabytes.@{par}

@endnode


@node LIMDOW "LIMDOW Media"

@{line}@{u}LIMDOW Media@{uu}@{par}

You may have heard of LIMDOW media. LIMDOW stands for @{i}Light Intensity
Modulation Direct OverWrite@{ui}, and is also known as "direct overwrite".@{par}

When using convential MO disks, in order for the drive to write a sector to
disk, it erases the sector, writes the new data, and then verifies the
just-written data. (You can enable or disable verification by using a DIP
switch on the drive, or by sending the appropriate command to the drive.) This
requires three revolutions of the disk.@{par}

With LIMDOW media and a LIMDOW-capable drive, the new data can be written with
no need for the old data to be erased first. This means that writing speed is
increased by about 50%. Without verification, writing speed would be almost
doubled.@{par}

The down side to this is that, at least for the moment, LIMDOW media is more
expensive than normal media.@{par}

@endnode


@node Backward_Compatibility "Backward Compatibility"

@{line}@{u}Backward Compatibility@{uu}@{par}

The first generation of 3½" MO drives could only use 128MB disks. Second
generation 230MB drives can read and write 128MB and 230MB disks. Current 640MB
3½" drives can read and write 128MB, 230MB, 540MB and 640MB disks (early 640MB
drives could not write to 128MB disks). 1.3GB drives have recently been
released by Fujitsu and Philips, and are read- and write-compatible with all
previous types of disk as well as the new 1.3GB "Gigamo" disks. You can read
about this drive on the @{"Fujitsu Europe web site" link Where_To_Get}.@{par}

Similarly, 5¼" MO drives are also backwardly compatible. First generation
600/650MB drives were available in 1989 or 1990. Later generations supported
1.2/1.3GB and then 2.3/2.6GB disks. Current drives can read and write
4.1/4.8/5.2GB disks, and most can at least read all older generations. Current
@{"Sony" link Where_To_Get} drives can only write to 2.3/2.6GB and
4.1/4.8/5.2GB disks, not the older 600/650MB and 1.2/1.3GB disks.
@{"Nikon" link Where_To_Get} drives can read and write all generations, from
600/650MB to 4.1/4.8/5.2GB.@{par}

@endnode


@node Media_Costs "Media Costs"

@{line}@{u}Media Costs@{uu}@{par}

Cost per megabyte of MO media is much lower than other removable media like
Zip, Jaz and LS120 disks. @{"LIMDOW media" link LIMDOW} is more expensive, but
still works out cheaper than other types of removable media.@{par}

This section illustrates the relative price differences between MO disks and
other types of removable media. It is not intended to be comprehensive or
up-to-date or to cover all countries, just as a guide to how much cheaper MO
disks are. Check a current computer magazine for up-to-date prices. Macintosh
magazines are likely to have more adverts for MO drives and disks than PC ones.@{par}

Here are some costs for various types of MO media in the UK. They are the
lowest prices that I have seen advertised. The prices below exclude 17.5% VAT
(sales tax), figures are in pounds sterling:@{code}

@{jcenter}@{u}@{b}Media type          Cost (£)  Cost/MB (p)@{ub}@{uu}
128MB 3½"               3        2.34    
230MB 3½"               3        1.30    
540MB 3¼"               5.50     1.02    
640MB 3½"               5.50     0.86    
640MB 3½" LIMDOW       12        1.88    
650MB 5¼"               9.50     1.46    
1.3GB 5¼"              10.50     0.81    
2.6GB 5¼"              18        0.69    
5.2GB 5¼"              47.50     0.91    @{par}@{body}@{jleft}

Compare these prices with typical media costs for other storage devices:@{code}

@{jcenter}@{u}@{b}Media type          Cost (£)  Cost/MB (p)@{ub}@{uu}
100MB Zip               6        6.00    
120MB LS120             6.70     5.58    
230MB SyQuest EZFlyer  15        8.70    
250MB Zip              12        4.80    
  1GB Jaz              50        5.00    
1.5GB SyJet            51        3.40    
  2GB Jaz              58        2.90    @{par}@{body}@{jleft}

If you're in the United States or Canada, two web sites which may be useful for
finding cheap MO media are @{fg shine}http://shopper.com/@{fg text} and
@{fg shine}http://www.pricewatch.com/@{fg text}.@{par}

Unlike proprietary systems like Zip and Jaz, MO drives and media are made by
many different manufacturers. This is partly why MO disks are so much cheaper.
With the Zip and Jaz, Iomega makes a large profit on the media allowing them to
sell the bare drives quite cheaply, whereas different manufacturers of MO media
are competing. MO disks are made by at least BASF, Dysan, Fujifilm, Fujitsu,
IBM, Imation (3M), Maxell, Maxoptix, Olympus, Philips, Ricoh, Sony, TDK and
Verbatim.@{par}

@endnode


@node Drive_Costs "Drive Costs"

@{line}@{u}Drive Costs@{uu}@{par}

MO drives are usually more expensive than similar capacity magnetic media
drives. However, given the low media cost, they will be more economical if you
have more than a couple of disks. Drives are commonly bundled with several
disks, making the cost very competitive with other removable media.@{par}

Compared with Iomega's recently released 250MB Zip drive, a 230MB MO drive is
the same price from some resellers.@{par}

For example, here are some MO drive prices in pounds sterling:@{code}

@{jcenter}Fujitsu 230MB internal                       100
Fujitsu 230MB with one 230MB disk            140
Philips MO 230 with one 230MB disk           140
Philips Pegasus MO 230 with ten 230MB disks  175
Fujitsu DynaMO 640SE with one 640MB disk     215
Philips MO 640 with one 640MB disk           200@{par}@{body}@{jleft}

Unless stated, these prices are for external SCSI drives; internal models cost
less, so if you have a tower case or a spare internal drive bay you can get one
of them. If your Amiga has an IDE/ATAPI controller, you can consider buying an
ATAPI rather than SCSI drive. But remember that with an external unit, you can
easily connect the MO drive up to a Mac or PC.@{par}

In comparison, buying other types of removable drive with this amount of
storage may cost significantly more; and of course magnetic removable media
does not have the same level of reliability as MO. Some example prices are:@{code}

@{jcenter}Zip 100MB with one disk                       70
SyQuest EZFlyer 230MB with one disk          100
Zip 250MB with one disk                      140
Jaz 1GB with one disk                        190
SyQuest SyJet 1.5GB with one disk            200
Jaz 2GB with one disk                        250@{par}@{body}@{jleft}

@endnode


@node Drive_Specifications "Drive Specifications"

@{line}@{u}Drive Specifications@{uu}@{par}

Modern 3½" 640MB MO drives are fast enough to be used as general storage or
like a hard disk. However, writes are slower than reads, and if you are
planning on using an MO disk for very write-intensive applications, you should
probably use @{"LIMDOW media" link LIMDOW} to speed up writes. For general
backup, file storage and running applications & games from, non-LIMDOW disks
are fine. Note that the seek time will not be as quick as most modern hard
disks.@{par}

Figures for Fujitsu's MCC3064SS and MCB3064SS 640MB 3½" MO drive mechanisms are
as follows:@{code}
@{jcenter}+--------------------+------------+-----------+-----------+-----------+
|@{b}Storage Capacity@{ub}    |    128MB   |   230MB   |   540MB   |   640MB   |
|--------------------+------------+-----------+-----------+-----------|
|@{b}Sector size (bytes)@{ub} |                 512                |   2048    |
|--------------------+------------+-----------+-----------+-----------|
|@{b}Transfer Rate (max)@{ub} |            |           |                       |
| @{b}3600rpm (MCC3064SS)@{ub}|  1.09MB/s  |1.3-2.1MB/s|      2.3-3.9MB/s      |
| @{b}4300rpm (MCB3064SS)@{ub}|  1.3MB/s   |1.6-2.5MB/s|      2.8-4.7MB/s      |
|                    |------------+-----------+-----------------------|
| @{b}Interface@{ub}          |            5MB/s async., 10MB/s sync.          |
|--------------------+------------------------------------------------|
|@{b}Seek Time@{ub}           |                                                |
| @{b}Random Seek@{ub}        |                  28ms typical                  |
| @{b}Full Stroke@{ub}        |                  60ms typical                  |
|--------------------+------------------------------------------------|
|@{b}Average Latency Time@{ub}|                                                |
| @{b}3600rpm (MCC3064SS)@{ub}|                     8.3ms                      |
| @{b}4300rpm (MCB3064SS)@{ub}|                     7.0ms                      |
|--------------------+------------------------------------------------|
|@{b}Rotational Speed@{ub}    |  3600rpm or 4300rpm depending on drive model   |
|--------------------+------------------------------------------------|
|@{b}Load/unload Time@{ub}    |                 7 sec./5 sec.                  |
|--------------------+------------------------------------------------|
|@{b}Buffer Size@{ub}         |                      2MB                       |
+--------------------+------------------------------------------------+@{pard}@{par}@{body}@{jleft}

Fujitsu's latest 3½" drives have an improved average seek time of 23ms.@{par}

Overall write speed will be about 1/3 of the maximum transfer rate for standard
disks with verification enabled. It is about 1/2 of the maximum when using
LIMDOW media with verification, or normal media without verification. Maximum
write speed is achieved with LIMDOW media and verification disabled.@{par}

The drive has 2MB of buffer RAM which improves read and write speeds. Operation
of the read-ahead cache can be seen when reading data from the drive; the
drive's own activity LED only flashes occasionally (corresponding to when data
is actually read from the disk), whereas the Amiga's SCSI activity LED is on
constantly (corresponding to data being transferred from drive to computer).
Earlier MO drives had less buffer RAM; the first 640MB drives had 512KB. Some
5¼" drives have 8MB.@{par}

There is also a @{"write-back cache" link About_Write_Cache} which can speed up
writes, especially small ones. You may wish to disable the write-back cache to
guarantee data integrity. However, there should not be a problem if you are
aware of how the cache works.@{par}

The read speed of my 640MB drive easily outpaces the capability of my
1991-vintage GVP SCSI controller. For writing, on my system I get over 1MB per
second using a direct overwrite 640MB disk, FFS 43.20 and DiskSpeed 4.2.@{par}

For specifications of other types of drive, consult the manufacturer's web
page.@{par}

@endnode


@node Maintenance "Maintenance"

@{line}@{u}Maintenance@{uu}@{par}

If you ever have trouble reading all disks on your MO drive, the drive lens may
need to be cleaned. Over time, dust settling on the lens can hinder the drive's
ability to read data. A cleaning cartridge for your drive will be available
from the drive manufacturer. It is very important to realise that the cleaning
cartridge is specific to each type of drive; you cannot use (say) a Sony
cleaning cartridge with a Fujitsu drive. Attempting to do so may damage the
drive.@{par}

If the problem is specific to a certain disk, the surface of that disk may need
cleaning. Fujitsu, IBM and Verbatim are three sources for these. Non-brand name
combined MO & Mini Disc disk cleaners are available very cheaply; less then 2
pounds.@{par}

Disk cleaners are quite simple to use. They basically consist of a jig into
which you put the MO disk, plus a cleaning cloth and solution. There is a notch
on the jig so that the disk shutter is held open. A knob in the centre of the
jig is turned to rotate the disk, and repeatedly wiping the exposed surface and
turning the knob cleans the whole surface.@{par}

Just how often you will need to clean your disks and drive depends on how dusty
an environment they are in, and how much they are used. In a domestic or office
setting, cleaning disks should only be needed very occasionally, and cleaning
the drive even less so. I have not needed to clean my drive or any disks since I
bought it in early 1998.@{par}

@endnode


@node Choosing "Choosing an MO Drive"

@{line}@{u}Choosing an MO Drive@{uu}@{par}

Once you have decided to buy an MO drive, which type should you choose? This
section contains some things which you need to consider.@{par}

What disk capacity do you need? Of course this depends on what you will be
using the drive for. For storing a large quantity of files downloaded from the
Internet, backing up a large collection of floppy disks, or large hard disk
partitions, using higher capacity disks can be much more convenient.@{par}

For professional use, a 2.6GB or 5.2GB 5¼" drive is a possibility. These drives
are widely used in professional audio and video applications, e.g. for
direct-to-disk audio recording. For most users, the cost of a new 5¼" drive
will be too high, though used older-generation drives are sometimes available
very cheaply.@{par}

This narrows it down to a 3½" unit; 230MB, 640MB or maybe one of the new 1.3GB
drives. Unsurprisingly, 1.3GB drives are considerably more expensive than 640MB
ones. Compared to 230MB drives, I think the higher cost of a 640MB drive is
well worth it, given the extra storage capacity and data transfer speed.@{par}

Which manufacturer's product should you buy? If you want a 1.3GB 3½" drive,
Fujitsu Europe recently released their DynaMO 1300SD external drive. Philips
will be selling a rebadged version of this. The Fujitsu DynaMO 640SE or
Philips MO 640 may be the best value 640MB external drives. The Fujitsu model
comes in a dark-coloured casing, while Philips' rebadged version has a
white/cream colour casing. Fujitsu also make a faster 3½" mechanism with a spin
speed of 4300rpm, compared to 3600rpm for their other drives. You may want to
investigate which companies sell units incorporating this faster mechanism; I
believe the DynaMO 640SE uses the slower 3600rpm drive.@{par}

Recently Fujitsu introduced a new line of 640MB drive mechanisms, which have an
improved seek time, 28ms average compared with 35ms for the older M2513 drives.
The new MCC3064 mechanism is used in the DynaMO 640SE, but some drives from
other companies may still use the older M2513 mechanism. Getting a drive with
the faster seek time is a good idea, especially if you are planning on using it
for intensive applications, e.g. use like a hard drive for booting from.@{par}

Olympus recently introduced their own external 640MB drive. I do not know how
much this costs, but it may be a good option.@{par}

The best (at least, going from the spec sheet) 230MB drive mechanism is made by
Olympus. External units are sold by Olympus and Philips; they are identical
apart from the case colour. This drive has a 4500rpm spin speed and 1MB cache.@{par}

@endnode


@node Where_To_Get "Where To Get More Information"

@{line}@{u}Where To Get More Information@{uu}@{par}

MO drives and disks are not as widely advertised in PC-oriented computer
magazines as things like @{"Zip and Jaz" link Zip_Jaz_Problems} drives.
I suggest you read the adverts in Macintosh magazines. A drive sold for
Macintosh use will come with Mac driver software, which can be used on the
Amiga with Macintosh emulators like @{"ShapeShifter" link Finding} and Fusion.@{par}

A group of MO drive and media manufacturers have created the MO Forum web site
at:@{code}
@{jcenter}@{fg shine}http://www.mo-forum.com/@{fg text}@{line}@{jleft}@{body}
This contains general information on MO technology, even if the English
version was clearly not written by a native English speaker...@{par}

Fujitsu make MO drives and media, including the DynaMO 640SE external SCSI
drive and 1.3GB internal and external drives. Most 640MB drives sold by other
companies use Fujitsu drive mechanisms. See Fujitsu's web sites at:@{code}
@{jcenter}@{fg shine}http://www.fujitsu-europe.com/
http://www.fcpa.com/
http://www.fujitsu.co.jp/@{fg text}@{par}@{jleft}@{body}

The Fujitsu Europe site includes extensive documentation for their drives in
PDF format; see the @{"For Programmers" link For_Programmers} section for the
URLs.@{par}

Philips PDO used to sell the Galaxy MO 640, a rebadged Fujitsu DynaMO 640 unit.
Their current @{"MO 640" link Images/640drive.jpg/main} is a rebadged Fujitsu
DynaMO 640SE. Typically the Philips drive is slightly cheaper than the
functionally identical Fujitsu one. Philips also sell a
@{"1.3GB drive" link Images/gimo.jpg/main}, which seems to be a rebadged
Fujitsu DynaMO 1300SD, and until recently sold a 230MB drive. Their web site is
at:@{code}
@{jcenter}@{fg shine}http://www.pdo.comp.philips.com/@{fg text}@{par}@{jleft}@{body}

Konica manufacture drives and media, and have an interesting web page which
describes various things they subjected an MO disk to, and how data was still
readable afterwards; e.g. soaking in coffee, dropping from second-floor window,
putting fingerprint on the disk surface. Their web site is at:@{code}
@{jcenter}@{fg shine}http://www.konica.co.jp/MO/index-e.html@{fg text}@{par}@{jleft}@{body}

Olympus' 230MB drive, the
@{"PowerMO 230II" link Images/PowerMO_230II_and_disk.jpg/main}, is identical to
the Philips 230MB drive, except in a different colour case. Their PowerMO 640
is a 640MB 3½" drive. Olypmus also sell an interesting product, the "dimo".
This allows their digital cameras to be connected to a PowerMO 230 drive for
storing images. Their web site is at:@{code}
@{jcenter}@{fg shine}http://www.olympus-europa.com/mo/@{fg text}@{par}@{jleft}@{body}

The Plasmon and Maxoptix web sites contain some general information on optical
storage which may be helpful, as well as information on their product ranges,
which are mainly targetted at professional markets. The URLs are:@{code}
@{jcenter}@{fg shine}http://www.plasmon.com/
http://www.plasmon.co.uk/
http://www.maxoptix.com/@{fg text}@{par}@{jleft}@{body}

LaCie, MaxOptix and Verbatim sell external 640MB 3½" drives, all using Fujitsu
drive mechanisms. The LaCie and Verbatim web sites are at:@{code}
@{jcenter}@{fg shine}http://www.lacie.com/
http://www.verbatimcorp.com/@{fg text}@{par}@{jleft}@{body}

Other MO drive manufacturers or OEMs are Canon, Epson, IBM, Mitsubishi,
Pinnacle Micro, Pioneer, Plasmon, Ricoh, Sharp, Sony, and Toshiba. In
particular, free Macintosh MO driver software can be downloaded from the
Pinnacle Micro web site at:@{code}
@{jcenter}@{fg shine}http://www.pinnaclemicro.com/@{fg text}@{par}@{jleft}@{body}

If you have contact/web site information for any other MO drive manufacturers,
please @{"contact me" link Contacting}.@{par}

If you have any Amiga-specific questions, feel free to ask on the
@{"Amiga MO mailing list" link Amiga_MO_Mailing_List}. Companies which sell MO
drives will almost certainly know nothing about the Amiga.@{par}

@endnode


@node Zip_Jaz_Problems "Zip & Jaz Reliability Problems"

@{line}@{u}Zip & Jaz Reliability Problems@{uu}@{par}

Magnetic media in general is not a good choice for reliability and long-term
data storage. However, the popular Zip and Jaz products from Iomega have had
some problems on top of this. If you are considering buying an Iomega Zip or
Jaz drive instead of an MO drive, you should know that many people have
reported reliability problems with these drives. You should investigate this
before making a decision.@{par}

Iomega have apparently admitted to a 10% failure rate for Jaz drives, and the
actual rate may be much higher. See@{code}
@{jcenter}@{fg shine}http://www.pinnaclemicro.com/solution.htm#storage@{fg text}
@{jleft}@{body}for some information on this.@{par}

Information about the "Zip click of death" syndrome can be found at the
Unofficial Iomega Click Death Page:@{code}
@{jcenter}@{fg shine}http://www.thirdeyesp.com/jatin/iomega/@{fg text}@{line}
@{jleft}@{body}You can find many more web pages about this by using a search
engine such as Altavista (@{fg shine}http://altavista.digital.com/@{fg text}),
to find pages which contain the words: Zip click death@{par}

Some time ago Iomega had to recall thousands of faulty Jaz disks because of a
manufacturing quality problem.@{par}

@endnode


@node Miscellaneous

@{line}@{u}Miscellaneous@{uu}@{par}

There are many products available for storing 3½" floppy disks. MO disks come
in individual hard plastic cases, though you could instead store them in a 3½"
disk box.@{par}

For portable storage, anything which holds an even number of 3½" floppy disks
on top of each other should hold 3½" MO disks nicely. For example, the aidata
"DiskToGo/2" product (model: 3502-4) is excellent for storing a single 3½" MO
disk. The Allsop "DiskFile 2" product is similar. These are probably sturdy
enough for sending MO disks by mail, but you should use a padded envelope in
any case. A box for holding ten 3½" floppy disks will hold five 3½" MO disks.@{par}

MO disks usually come with a two stick-on labels. If you run out of labels,
there is no problem; standard 3½" floppy disk labels fit nicely.@{par}

@endnode


@node Amiga_Requirements "Amiga Requirements"

@{line}@{u}Amiga Requirements@{uu}@{par}

This section describes what hardware and software you need to have in order to
use an MO drive.@{par}

@{line}@{b}Hardware Requirements@{ub}@{par}

You need a SCSI controller in order to use a SCSI drive.@{par}

There are MO drives available which use the IDE/ATAPI interface, for example
Fujitsu's MCA3064AP 640MB drive. It is probably possible to use these with an
A1200 or A4000's built-in IDE controller in conjunction with software like
"IDEfix", but I have not tried this.@{par}

@{line}@{b}Software Requirements@{ub}@{par}

No special software is needed.@{par}

For using media with sector size other than 512 bytes, for example 640MB or
1.3GB 3½" disks, you will need to use FastFileSystem version 40.1 or later,
which is in the Kickstart 3.1 ROM, and on the AmigaOS 3.1 Install disk.@{par}

FFS 40.1 is compatible with Kickstarts 1.2 & 1.3, so it is probably possible to
use 640MB or 1.3GB 3½" MO disks under even these old operating systems. I have
not tested this; perhaps the only problem will be in finding a suitable
1.x-compatible Mount command. It will definitely be possible to use 512-byte
sectors MO media with these old OS versions and almost any FFS version, or the
ROM OFS.@{par}

You can download the latest beta version of the FastFileSystem from the Amiga
Inc. web site at:@{code}
@{jcenter}@{fg shine}http://www.amiga.de/@{fg text}@{par}@{jleft}@{body}

I am currently using FFS 43.20 with my 640MB MO drive. The beta FFS versions
seem to require at least AmigaOS 3.1. Alternatively, you can use another
filesystem such as @{"SFS" link Finding} or PFS2. If using disks with a sector
size other than 512 bytes, make sure that whichever filesystem you use supports
that sector size! PFS2 does not @{i}officially@{ui} support sector sizes
greater than 1024 bytes.@{par}

If you want to use HDToolBox to create RDBs on your MO disks, be aware that
HDToolBox only allows RDBs to be installed on direct access devices, i.e. hard
disks. See the @{"Drive Settings (DIP switches)" link Drive_Settings} section
for more information on the two selectable device types. I have created a
@{"patch for HDToolBox" link HDToolBox_Patch} to allow you to use HDToolBox
with MO drives that are set to "optical memory device" mode.@{par}

For information on reading and writing PC and Macintosh-formatted MO disks and
using the drive under @{"ShapeShifter" link Finding}, see the
@{"Cross-Platform Access" link Cross-Platform} section and the
@{"mount files" link Mount_Files}.@{par}

SCSI utility programs such as @{"SCSIUtil" link Finding} can be used to eject
the disk, instead of having to press the Eject button on the drive. You can
prevent and allow manual disk ejection with the same program. See the
@{"example scripts" link Example_Scripts}.@{par}

I have not tried using a large capacity 5¼" MO drive or disks with my Amiga.
However, all current sizes are unlikely to be a problem. Remember that 5¼"
disks are double-sided, and you turn over the disk to access the other half
capacity. So with a 5.2GB MO disk, each side holds 2.6GB of data. There are
none of the problems associated with hard disks larger than 4GB. Some programs
including HDToolBox may get confused and report negative amounts of space free,
but this should be harmless, and happens with any drive/partition over 2GB.@{par}

For use with alternative operating systems such as NetBSD, you may need to use
media with 512-byte sectors if the OS only supports this sector size. You may
not be able to use 640MB 3½" MO disks for example, since they have 2048-byte
sectors. You can use 540MB disks instead.@{par}

@endnode


@node Drive_Settings "Drive Settings (DIP switches)"

@{line}@{u}Drive Settings (DIP switches)@{uu}@{par}

To set up an MO drive for use on your Amiga, you need to set the following
options using the MO drive's DIP switches:@{line}
@{lindent 4}@{pari -2}@{par}· Set the SCSI ID to one which is not currently in
use.@{line}@{par}
· You may need to set the @{"device type" link Device_Type} to "direct access",
if your SCSI controller driver is old or badly written.@{line}@{par}
· Set "Macintosh mode" to off. I don't know what this setting means exactly,
but my drive works okay with this switch off. I have not tried it when the Mac
mode switch is on. According to Fujitsu: "Because of the differing ways that
both Apple Macintosh and PC hosts respond to the status of the drive, set this
switch accordingly. Mac mode ON will disable the 'UNIT ATTENTION' reporting on
power up and media change."@{line}@{par}
· If your drive supports SCAM (which stands for @{i}SCSI Configured
AutoMatically@{ui}), disable this feature.@{line}@{par}
· Enable or disable termination depending on whether your MO drive is the last
device in the SCSI chain. You may want to leave the disable the drive's
termination and use an external active SCSI terminator instead. This may be
necessary if your SCSI chain is very long.@{line}@{par}
· Consider whether you want to have the write-back cache enabled. By default,
most drives have it enabled. Generally, having it enabled should not cause any
problems, but see the @{"About the Write-Back Cache" link About_Write_Cache} section
for more information.@{line}@{par}
· Set the verify mode. When disabled, the speed of write operations is improved
by approximately 50%, however data integrity cannot be guaranteed. The
improvement when using @{"LIMDOW media" link LIMDOW} is about 100%. I recommend
that you @{b}always enable verify mode@{ub}.@{pard}@{par}

@endnode


@node Device_Type "Setting the Device Type"

@{line}@{u}Setting the Device Type@{uu}@{par}

MO drives usually have a DIP switch to set the device type mode. Depending on
how this is set, the drive reports itself as a @{i}direct access device@{ui} (type
0, the normal value for hard disks), or as an @{i}optical memory device@{ui} (type
7, the normal value for optical disks). In the absence of problems, it is
probably best to set the device type to optical memory.@{par}

Some programs, especially those that access SCSI drives directly, may check the
device type and refuse to work with drives of type other than zero. Commodore's
HDToolBox is an example of this, though I have developed a
@{"patch" link HDToolBox_Patch} to get around this problem. Some SCSI drivers
might refuse to boot from non-type-0 devices. My old GVP controller does not
have this problem.@{par}

The ShapeShifter Macintosh emulator refuses to boot from non-type-0 devices.
You can @{"patch ShapeShifter" link ShapeShifter_Patch} to fix this problem.@{par}

Apart from the reported device type, in direct access mode two hard disk mode
pages are returned, which are not returned in optical memory mode. They are:
@{lindent 4}@{pari -2}@{par}· format device (page 3)@{par}
· fixed disk geometry (page 4)@{pard}@{par}

The values for number of cylinders, heads and sectors per track given in these
two pages are "fake", for compatibility with PCs. For example, for 640MB
disks, the geometry values reported in the device format and rigid disk
parameter pages are 606 cylinders, 8 heads and 64 sectors per track, which
implies that the total number of sectors is 606×8×64 = 310272. The actual
number of sectors is 310352; some hard disk partitioning programs may use the
606×8×64 value instead of working out values based on the total disk size.@{par}

@endnode


@node Mounting_and_Using "Mounting and Using the Drive and Disks"

@{line}@{u}Mounting and Using the Drive and Disks@{uu}@{par}

Using a @{"mount file" link Mount_Files} to access the drive is the best option
if you want to use the MO disk for general data storage, and not for booting
from. This gives the maximum amount of free disk space, and disks formatted
like this will be easily interchangeable between Amigas.@{par}

If you want to boot from an MO disk, you must create an RDB (Rigid Disk Block)
on the disk, just as you would with a SCSI hard drive. You can use HDToolBox or
another hard disk partitioning program to do this. Using the RDB method, you
can create several partitions on a single MO disk. Many partitioning programs
come up with their own "fake" values for Cylinders, Heads and BlocksPerTrack,
which mean that some space is wasted. This can also cause problems if you use
two different partitioning programs, which use different sets of fake values.
Rather than accepting the program's defaults, you should adjust the values for
Cylinders, Heads and BlocksPerTrack so that:@{code}
@{jcenter}@{b}Cylinders@{ub} × @{b}Heads@{ub} × @{b}BlocksPerTrack@{ub} = @{b}total number of sectors on disk@{ub}@{par}@{jleft}@{body}
To find suitable values for these parameters, refer to the prime factors in the
table below. For other types of disk you can use @{"PFactor" link Finding}.@{par}

If you reduce the (logical) number of blocks per track, the RDB will take up
less space on the disk. Be careful not to make it too small though, in case you
decide to add another filesystem in future; the RDB may be too small to hold
it.@{par}

Hopefully an example will clarify this. 640MB disks have 310352 sectors.
310352 = 2×2×2×2×7×17×163, so some suitable values for Cylinders, Heads and
BlocksPerTrack might be@{code}
@{jcenter}Cylinders = 17×163 = 2771,  Heads = 2,       BlocksPerTrack = 2×2×2×7 = 56@{line}@{jleft}@{body}
or@{code}
@{jcenter}Cylinders = 2×7×163 = 2282, Heads = 2×2 = 4, BlocksPerTrack = 2×17 = 34   @{par}@{jleft}@{body}

HDToolbox needs to be @{"patched" link HDToolBox_Patch} if you want to use it
with your MO drive in "optical memory device" mode.@{par}

Mount files for PC-formatted disks (AT-HD type) may not use the entire disk
space; see the @{"mount files" link Mount_Files} for PC disks.@{par}

Here are tables of the number of usable sectors for each type of 3½" MO disk,
and each type of 5¼" disk:@{code}

@{jcenter}@{b}3½" disks@{ub}                                                    
+---------+-------------+-------------+---------------------+
|  Disk   | Sector size |  Number of  |  Prime factors of   |
|  type   |   (bytes)   |   sectors   |  number of sectors  |
|---------+-------------+-------------+---------------------|
|  128MB  |             |    248,826  |     2×3×113×367     |
|---------+             |-------------+---------------------|
|  230MB  |      512    |    446,325  |     3×5×5×11×541    |
|---------+             |-------------+---------------------|
|  540MB  |             |  1,041,500  |    2×2×5×5×5×2083   |
|---------+-------------+-------------+---------------------|
|  640MB  |    2,048    |    310,352  |   2×2×2×2×7×17×163  |
+---------+-------------+-------------+---------------------+
|  1.3GB  |    2,048    |    605,846  |     2×17×103×173    |
+---------+-------------+-------------+---------------------+

@{b}5¼" disks@{ub}                                                    
+---------+-------------+-------------+---------------------+
|  Disk   | Sector size |  Number of  |  Prime factors of   |
|  type   |   (bytes)   |   sectors   |  number of sectors  |
|---------+-------------+-------------+---------------------|
|  600MB  |      512    |    576,999  |     3×3×61×1051     |
|---------+-------------|-------------+---------------------|
|  650MB  |    1,024    |    314,569  |        314569       |
|---------+-------------|-------------+---------------------|
|  1.2GB  |      512    |  1,163,337  |     3×7×31×1787     |
|---------+-------------+-------------+---------------------|
|  1.3GB  |    1,024    |    637,041  |      3×17×12491     |
+---------+-------------+-------------+---------------------|
|  2.3GB  |      512    |  2,244,958  |      2×31×36209     |
+---------+-------------+-------------+---------------------|
|  2.6GB  |    1,024    |  1,273,011  |     3×17×109×229    |
+---------+-------------+-------------+---------------------|
|  4.1GB  |      512    |  3,973,952  | 2×2×2×2×2×2×31×2003 |
+---------+-------------+-------------+---------------------|
|  4.8GB  |    1,024    |  2,319,786  |  2×3×3×3×7×17×19×19 |
+---------+-------------+-------------+---------------------|
|  5.2GB  |    2,048    |  1,263,472  |   2×2×2×2×7×29×389  |
+---------+-------------+-------------+---------------------+@{body}@{par}@{jleft}


There are several @{"mount files" link Mount_Files} in the DOSDrivers-3½ and
DOSDrivers-5¼ drawers which are part of the Amiga MO FAQ distribution. You can
modify these if you need to create a mount file for other filesystems such as
PFS2.@{par}

@{b}TO CREATE SOME KIND OF STANDARD FOR AMIGA-FORMATTED MO DISKS, ALWAYS USE 2
RESERVED BLOCKS@{ub}.@{par}

The exact values of Cylinders, Surfaces, HighCyl and BlocksPerTrack are not
important, provided that:@{code}
@{jcenter}@{b}Surfaces@{ub} × @{b}BlocksPerTrack@{ub} × (@{b}HighCyl@{ub}+1) = @{b}total number of sectors on disk@{ub}@{par}@{jleft}@{body}

For 640MB 3½" disks, this means that:@{code}
@{jcenter}@{b}Surfaces@{ub} × @{b}BlocksPerTrack@{ub} × (@{b}HighCyl@{ub}+1) = @{b}310352@{ub}@{par}@{jleft}@{body}

This is to ensure that MO disks are easily interchangeable between different
Amigas. If @{b}Surfaces@{ub} × @{b}BlocksPerTrack@{ub} × (@{b}HighCyl@{ub}+1)
is less than the number of sectors in the disk, you waste disk space, and would
need to also send a copy of your mount file when sending an MO disk to someone.@{par}

If you use a mount file to mount the drive, you can use MO disks just as you
would floppy disks. Ejecting and inserting a new disk should be automatically
detected by the Amiga.@{par}

If you insert an MO disk with RDB after booting your Amiga, you will need to
use a program such as @{"SCSIMounter" link Finding} in order to mount the
partition(s) on that disk.@{par}

It's easy to format a new MO disk for use. If using a mount file, you can just
insert the disk and type a command like:@{code}
@{jcenter}Format DRIVE MO0: NAME "My MO disk" NOICONS FFS QUICK@{par}@{jleft}@{body}
(Replace MO0: with whatever drive name you have mounted MO disks of that
capacity as.) The MO disk will be ready for use in a couple of seconds. It is
not necessary to do a full format (i.e., not to use the QUICK option), but you
can if you want.@{par}

You may wish to perform a @{"low-level format" link Low-Level} on your MO disks
at some point. This is advisable if you buy uncertified disks.@{par}

@endnode


@node Different_Capacities "Using Different Disk Capacities"

@{line}@{u}Using Different Disk Capacities@{uu}@{par}

As mentioned in the @{"Types of MO Media" link Types_of_MO_Media} section, MO
drives can use several different capacities of disk. Since there is currently
no @{"special MO driver software" link For_Programmers} for the Amiga, it is
not possible to access different capacity MO disks using the same device name
(but see @{"Mounting and Using the Drive and Disks" link Mounting_and_Using}).@{par}

On my Amiga, I mount the MO0: device to access 640MB MO disks. To access 128MB,
230MB or 540MB media, I would have to use other mount files, e.g. for devices
@{"MO128:" link DOSDrivers-3½/FFS/MO128/Main},
@{"MO230:" link DOSDrivers-3½/FFS/MO230/Main} and
@{"MO540:" link DOSDrivers-3½/FFS/MO540/Main}, in order to access disks of these
capacities. This is not a major problem, since you will probably mostly use
disks of the highest capacity your drive can handle. See the
@{"mount files" link Mount_Files}.@{par}

@endnode


@node Mount_Files "Mount Files"

@{line}@{u}Mount Files@{uu}@{par}

Here are mount files for several different filesystems and disk types. Drag the
icons for the mount files you want to install to DEVS:DOSDrivers or
SYS:Storage/DOSDrivers, and set the DEVICE and UNIT tooltypes, and the Mask and
MaxTransfer values appropriately for your system. Please
@{"contact me" link Contacting} if you have problems with any of these mount
files.@{par}

@{line}@{b}Amiga FFS@{ub}@{line}
After mounting an FFS volume, you can use the Format command to set the DosType
just as you would a floppy disk or hard disk partition. For example:@{code}
@{jcenter}Format DRIVE MO640: NAME "My MO Disk" NOICONS FFS DIRCACHE QUICK
@{b}3½"@{ub}
@{"     FFS 128MB     " link DOSDrivers-3½/FFS/MO128/Main}
@{"     FFS 230MB     " link DOSDrivers-3½/FFS/MO230/Main}
@{"     FFS 540MB     " link DOSDrivers-3½/FFS/MO540/Main}
@{"     FFS 640MB     " link DOSDrivers-3½/FFS/MO640/Main}
@{"     FFS 1.3GB     " link DOSDrivers-3½/FFS/MO1300/Main}
@{b}5¼"@{ub}
@{"     FFS 600MB     " link DOSDrivers-5¼/FFS/MO600/Main}
@{"     FFS 650MB     " link DOSDrivers-5¼/FFS/MO650/Main}
@{"     FFS 1.2GB     " link DOSDrivers-5¼/FFS/MO1.2/Main}
@{"     FFS 1.3GB     " link DOSDrivers-5¼/FFS/MO1.3/Main}
@{"     FFS 2.3GB     " link DOSDrivers-5¼/FFS/MO2.3/Main}
@{"     FFS 2.6GB     " link DOSDrivers-5¼/FFS/MO2.6/Main}
@{"     FFS 4.1GB     " link DOSDrivers-5¼/FFS/MO4.1/Main}
@{"     FFS 4.8GB     " link DOSDrivers-5¼/FFS/MO4.8/Main}
@{"     FFS 5.2GB     " link DOSDrivers-5¼/FFS/MO5.2/Main}@{par}@{jleft}@{body}

@{line}@{b}Amiga SFS@{ub}@{line}
@{"SFS" link Finding} is a new filesystem for the Amiga, developed by John
Hendrikx. It is currently in beta testing, so I don't recommend that you use it
for storage of important data yet. The current beta version of SFS is supposed
to automatically support detection of different disk capacities, but this does
not seem to work properly. There is an SFS support web page at
@{fg shine}http://www.xs4all.nl/~hjohn/SFS/@{fg text}.@{code}
@{jcenter}@{b}3½"@{ub}
@{"     SFS 128MB     " link DOSDrivers-3½/SFS/SFS128/Main}
@{"     SFS 230MB     " link DOSDrivers-3½/SFS/SFS230/Main}
@{"     SFS 540MB     " link DOSDrivers-3½/SFS/SFS540/Main}
@{"     SFS 640MB     " link DOSDrivers-3½/SFS/SFS640/Main}
@{"     SFS 1.3GB     " link DOSDrivers-3½/SFS/SFS1300/Main}
@{b}5¼"@{ub}
@{"     SFS 600MB     " link DOSDrivers-5¼/SFS/SFS600/Main}
@{"     SFS 650MB     " link DOSDrivers-5¼/SFS/SFS650/Main}
@{"     SFS 1.2GB     " link DOSDrivers-5¼/SFS/SFS1.2/Main}
@{"     SFS 1.3GB     " link DOSDrivers-5¼/SFS/SFS1.3/Main}
@{"     SFS 2.3GB     " link DOSDrivers-5¼/SFS/SFS2.3/Main}
@{"     SFS 2.6GB     " link DOSDrivers-5¼/SFS/SFS2.6/Main}
@{"     SFS 4.1GB     " link DOSDrivers-5¼/SFS/SFS4.1/Main}
@{"     SFS 4.8GB     " link DOSDrivers-5¼/SFS/SFS4.8/Main}
@{"     SFS 5.2GB     " link DOSDrivers-5¼/SFS/SFS5.2/Main}@{par}@{jleft}@{body}

@{line}@{b}PC-compatible MS-DOS FAT@{ub} (requires CrossDOS)@{line}
It should be possible to use the following mount file with any AT-HD formatted
disk, no matter what the partition layout. Mounting MOC: will access the first
partition on the disk. To access other partitions, you need to copy and rename
MOC to MOD, MOE, etc. CrossDOS determines which partition to mount by looking
at the last letter of the device name; C for the first partition, D for the
second and so on. This mount file is based on the one on Aminet as
disk/misc/mount_msdos.lha, which was created by Dirk Eismann and Volker Remuß.@{code}
@{jcenter}@{"  PC AT-HD (MOC:)  " link DOSDrivers-3½/PC/MOC/Main}@{par}@{jleft}@{body}

These AT-HD type mount files can be used with disks which have been formatted
on a PC, with a single partition. CrossDOS is not able to format disks of this
type, but you can read and write them. It is probably better to use the MOC
DOSDriver above, since that does not depend on a certain partition layout.@{code}
@{jcenter}@{"  PC AT-HD 128MB   " link DOSDrivers-3½/PC/PC128/Main}
@{"  PC AT-HD 230MB   " link DOSDrivers-3½/PC/PC230/Main}
@{"  PC AT-HD 540MB   " link DOSDrivers-3½/PC/PC540/Main}@{par}@{jleft}@{body}

These mount files can be used to access disks in "superfloppy" format. The
difference between PC AT-HD and superfloppy disk is similar to that between RDB
and mount file disks on the Amiga.@{code}
@{jcenter}@{b}3½"@{ub}
@{" Superfloppy 128MB " link DOSDrivers-3½/PC/SF128/Main}
@{" Superfloppy 230MB " link DOSDrivers-3½/PC/SF230/Main}
@{" Superfloppy 540MB " link DOSDrivers-3½/PC/SF540/Main}
@{" Superfloppy 640MB " link DOSDrivers-3½/PC/SF640/Main}
@{" Superfloppy 1.3GB " link DOSDrivers-3½/PC/SF1300/Main}
@{b}5¼"@{ub}
@{" Superfloppy 600MB " link DOSDrivers-5¼/PC/SF600/Main}
@{" Superfloppy 650MB " link DOSDrivers-5¼/PC/SF650/Main}
@{" Superfloppy 1.2GB " link DOSDrivers-5¼/PC/SF1.2/Main}
@{" Superfloppy 1.3GB " link DOSDrivers-5¼/PC/SF1.3/Main}
@{" Superfloppy 2.3GB " link DOSDrivers-5¼/PC/SF2.3/Main}
@{" Superfloppy 2.6GB " link DOSDrivers-5¼/PC/SF2.6/Main}
